.TH GIT-STAGE-BATCH-APPLY 1 "May 2026" "git-stage-batch @VERSION@" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
git-stage-batch-apply \- apply batch changes to the working tree
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B git-stage-batch apply
\fB\-\-from\fR \fIBATCH\fR
[\fB\-\-line\fR \fIIDS\fR]
[\fB\-\-file\fR [\fIPATH\fR] | \fB\-\-files\fR \fIPATTERN\fR...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B apply
applies changes from a batch to the working tree without staging them. The
batch remains available after the command.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI "\-\-from " BATCH
Apply changes from
.IR BATCH .
To apply a reviewed ambiguity resolution, use
.IR BATCH :apply: N
with
.BR \-\-file .
The
.IR BATCH :include: N
selector belongs to
.B include
and is rejected here.
.TP
.BI "\-\-line, \-\-lines " IDS
Apply only specific displayed line IDs.
.TP
.B \-\-file
.RI [ PATH ]
Apply one file from the batch. If
.I PATH
is omitted, use the selected batch file when available.
.TP
.BI "\-\-files " PATTERN "..."
Apply batch files matched by gitignore-style patterns.
.SH CANDIDATES
If a plain
.B apply --from
operation finds multiple safe structural placements, it refuses without
changing the working tree and points to
.B show --from
.IR BATCH :apply .
Review the candidate overview, or preview a numbered candidate, then apply
that same reviewed candidate:
.RS
.nf
git-stage-batch show --from cleanup:apply --file src/app.py
git-stage-batch show --from cleanup:apply:2 --file src/app.py
git-stage-batch apply --from cleanup:apply:2 --file src/app.py
.fi
.RE
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR git-stage-batch (1),
.BR git-stage-batch-include (1),
.BR git-stage-batch-discard (1)
